A lot of race teams and riders use @rideengineeringinc clamps like we spoke about last @pulpmxshow. Ride Eng. is constantly testing its products and making updates so that they can evolve with the motorcycle manufactures’ new chassis. Triple clamps used to be only about changing how the bike handles, but now the front end feel, the steering precision and the comfort all play a big part in making a triple clamp better than stock. Don’t think the expensive price tag is about looks, it’s about using the best materials and longer machining times to put all the details in that can be felt on the track. Ok, I have a few rides on the e-bike specific @ridespinergy wheels to talk about them. The guys there are finding lots of customers bending and folding std E-bike wheels so they’ve designed a set that’s a little burlier. Featuring their PBO flexy spokes, that kind of blows your mind when u see how much they bend! These wheels are a bit heavier than what I came off of and I noticed that immediately. They also, because of the flexy spokes (they call them PBO spokes) the ride was smoother and I got less chatter. In fact I was able to go in on compression on fork to get some more “feel” back. Also could hammer through rocks easier and not feel it as much. I had to honestly check AP in rear as well because it’s so cushy of a ride. Makes a big difference with these spokes. The hub is beefy as well, the rim is carbon and I think they look cool also. Not a fan of having to buy center lock discs tho but that’s their only option. All in all, a well built set of wheels that I will think would last a long time and also, it will take some getting used to with this tech. Use the code pulpmx @ridespinergy to save 20% off a set of these wheels or regular ones as well!

As we talked about on @pulpmxshow Monday night, the guys @rideengineeringinc have realized that with an all new YZ450 chassis, its only fitting that Ride Engineering redesigned their Yamaha triple clamps around this model. The lower clamp is now less rigid in bumps and chop while retaining the steering precision you expect from a billet triple clamp. Its available in 3 offsets, 20mm, 22mm (stock) and 23.5mm. Ride recommends either the stock or 23.5 offsets for moto and the 20s for Supercross/Arenacross. For $649/set its not just your wallet that’s lighter as they save 1/2lb over stock. Check them out at www.ride-engineering.com and use pulpfan20 to save.

As we talked last Monday on @pulpmxshow, @rideengineeringinc steering damper kits are in stock and make a bigger difference on the new 2023-24 KTM & Husqvarna frames that the previous generations. Weight bias has been moved causing more wiggle under hard acceleration and when entering corners with uneven bumps. The new bracket assembly installs in minutes as the upper triple clamp no longer gets removed. With four Showa dampers to choose from, this is a very clean damper assembly that goes behind the number plate. Steering is unhindered except when you need some extra resistance to slow deflection. Check these out at www.ride-engineering.com and use pulpfan20 to save on the bracket assembly.

Found this old photo of me in KTM days to throw up but hey everyone, thanks for listening and reading all my stuff throughout the years and I thought I’d make a post to talk about this recent “thing” out there in the internet. The amount of vile posts/DM’s I’ve been getting have set me off on the path to posting this. As I said on the show, the amount of money and time I’ve spent to get into this country proves that I want to be here and like all of you, I have a right to express my opinion. Which was that I hate, HATE, to see the numerous foreign riders get flipped off on the podium. We’re all here for motocross, we love motocross and if you think flipping riders off that happen to be from another country is cool, then this isn’t for you. But I’m betting you don’t like it. I don’t remember Ken Roczen or Chad Reed’s competitors dropping a USA angle on the podium at a national and I’m simply afraid that the way this country is so divided right now, the Lawrence family (who have not given me any interviews in months by the way) will start to see hostility at the podium. Which sucks, as I also said-they’re the epitome of the American dream! They sold everything, sacrificed everything to come to this country and race motocross. NEVER did I say I didn’t like it here, NEVER did I say USA sucks (but what I’ve learned is you MAGA people cry a lot and can try to cancel people just like the loonies on the left)…the shit posts, the shit DM’s from people who didn’t actually listen to what I said and joined the mob, hope you feel good about yourself doing exactly what you say the other side does which is spreading hate and I would just say “Be better”. If you understand what I said and disagree like Weege and JT did (but they both got where I was coming from), no problem at all. That’s what makes America what it is. I’ll continue to talk/write about the sport I love & try to make people think about things. I’ll continue to also discuss things that others may not. Thanks for coming to my Ted Talk.

The @flyracingusa @racerxonline LA SMX race review pod with @jasonweigandt & @jason66thomas is up! Presented by @renthal_moto @maxxistires @koubalinks & @motosportinc we dive into all aspects of the race both good and bad. It was cool to be back at the Coliseum, Kawi, A Stars and Yamaha had events built around this race and the pits were packed. Did the SMX series work? Well, I’d say so but it wasn’t a home run in my eyes, I did sense some fatigue from the teams. The term playoffs should mean something also in terms of riders getting eliminated from title contention. 31 races in 37 weekends (ish) is a lot and not one factory rider made every race due to injuries. Which should say something right? The money paid to the racers and teams in some cases is a good thing ultimately as is the cooperation of MX Sports and Feld. Looking back at it now, how dumb was it that SX and MX promoters couldn’t work together right? What a year 2023 was as well. I’m tired and need some time off! Why doesn’t anyone think of the poor media? 🤣🤣

A couple things have changed the sport forever since I started going to the races in ‘96. One is four-strokes the elimination of mistakes by the riders- watch any old video and you can see even the greats sometimes have to back out of triples and quads because they screw up the corner. That’s mostly gone. I accidentally stumbled onto something on a Pulpmx Show a year ago or so. I started looking thru qualifying times in SX around the RV/Dunge era and there were huge gaps back to tenth, sometimes 4-5 seconds. Now tho, with advances in bike tech, many guys riding at facilities, training the same way as any of the top riders, there are no secrets really. So the edge of the knife gets thinner and thinner every so often. We are now at the point where top ten guys qualify within a second of each other. It’s crazy. So I asked our guy @mxreference if he could run some numbers on how much the gap has shrunk and it turns out, he already did it! Go check out his IG page, give him a follow, and see how the gap has become so much smaller between the very best and then the “just great fucking riders”. Check it out!

Story time: I’ve only been to Loretta’s once, in ‘98 to work Honda support after my rider at FMF Honda, Danny Smith, got hurt. But while I was there turns out there was an industry race, IDK when it started or when it ended, ask @dcracerx- but the guys at Honda of Houston rounded up a bike for me from some guy. It was a big bore CR250 and vibrated like crazy (old CR aluminum frame, I think it was a 330cc). I think I borrowed some gear for this (clearly grabbed a FMF jersey from the support truck) and IDK how I did but I remember @rr67 was in the race, maybe Dement also? Anyways the real funny part was “the guy” whose bike I borrowed was @tdf_thomas who about 13 years later became a good friend of mine! Nuts right? Thomas sent me this photo today asking if this was me. Good times!!
